<br>
I knelt down, picked it up, looked at it fondly -- the soft crash of the sea, the sounds of Kerran children playing in the distance, the memory of the first time I found peace. I earned the necklace playing exterminator for the Kerrans. It wasn't glamourous work, but it was honest. <br>
<br>
I looked up at the banker, a gnoll, who was staring at me impatiently. <br>
<br>
&quot;Could I have a moment?&quot; I asked him. He grunted something about spacey half-elves and wandered off. <br>
<br>
I replaced the necklace in the safe and began to explore. <br>
<br>
I keep a Northman's long dagger wrapped in my old green apprentice's tunic. I bought the dagger from a babarian blacksmith named Caillach when I was just a boy. My first trip to Halas, when Pragger and Bonwhyn led me there, to my father's homeland. I sat around a fire long into the night and told my story to an elf, an Erudite and a Halasman. <br>
<br>
I rewrapped the dagger in my old shirt and placed it alongside all the other mementos I will never part with. <br>
<br>
The crystal fibre, given to me by a ranger named Savah on my first trip to Freeport simply because she was kind and I was struggling. A flint-headed spear I bought from the infamous Maladominus, when I was still ignorant of how infamous he was. The beautiful and functionally useless Sarnak sword I bought from a bard in Butcherblock. I still have never seen a Sarnak. <br>
<br>
The shardwurm tooth I took from my one and only hunt with Nehlurra. A warthread kilt, taken from a barbarian who attempted to kill me among the peaks in Everfrost. I washed it out and wore it for a time when I tried to uncover how my father must have lived. <br>
<br>
The compass I still carry, because I am forever getting lost. I think I'm the only ranger who carries a compass. And I'm no longer ashamed of that. <br>
<br>
The pair of blue boots, made of supple hopperhide, given to me by Siava, too fine to ever wear into battle, but sitting in an esteemed place in my safe. <br>
<br>
The machete Kimaya carted me around Luclin to retrieve. Another weapon of little use in battle, but resting comfortably next to a bow I made myself and no longer used. I used that bow to complete the task assigned to me to become a member of the Bastion. <br>
<br>
The moment I requested dragged on for much longer, but the gnoll let me be. There was no one else in his bank anyway, in a quiet cave in Jagged Pine. I sat for a long, long time, looking at the bits of the past I had never and would never cast away. <br>
<br>
Because I knew change was coming for me, felt it in my bones, and it worried me. And I wanted one last moment with my past before everything was torn apart. <br>
<br>
<br>
-Lest-ye-forget Ravenfolly<br>
ranger, wanderer, sometimes pacifist<br>
